---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Data Vizes with Bricks | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="A hands-on morning building data visualizations out of LEGO — bring your own dataset or use one of ours."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: Data Vizes with Bricks — October 3rd
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Oct 3 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Gamezenter</span
                        ><br />1975 County Road B2 W · Roseville, MN 55113</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                What if a bar chart had studs?
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a hands-on
                morning building data visualizations out of LEGO. Bricks are a
                weirdly perfect medium for data: they snap to a grid, they stack
                into bars, they come in fixed colors and sizes, and a 1×1 brick is
                a ready-made unit of one.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The premise is simple: <strong>bring your own dataset or use one
                of ours, and build a data visualization with it.</strong> Pick
                something small, decide what's worth showing, and make it in
                bricks — solo or alongside whoever's at your table. You leave with
                a thing you built, and a much sharper eye for what makes an
                encoding work.
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12 mb-8">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <img
                        src="/images/lego-rainbow-mosaic.jpeg"
                        alt="A dense rainbow mosaic of LEGO bricks, plates, and flower pieces arranged in a gradient from red through green to blue and purple"
                        class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                    />
                </div>
            </div>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                No bricks or data of your own? Come anyway — we'll have plenty of
                both. Anyone curious about data visualization is welcome,
                whether you work in D3, Tableau, ggplot2, Observable, or none of
                the above. Kids welcome!
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                More details to come as we get closer.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
